@node Annotation cleanup
@section Annotation cleanup

@findex org-noter-extras-cleanup-annotation
After running @code{org-noter-create-skeleton} to generate annotations from PDF highlights, each annotation gets a generic heading like ``Highlight on page 42'' with the extracted text in a child ``Contents'' heading. The command @code{org-noter-extras-cleanup-annotation} transforms this into a more useful format:

@enumerate
@item
It synchronizes the current note position with the PDF viewer.
@item
It switches to the Org notes buffer.
@item
It prompts you for a descriptive title for the annotation.
@item
It extracts the text content from the ``Contents'' subheading, running dehyphenation and filling the text to remove PDF line breaks.
@item
It replaces the generic heading with the supplied title (without any page-number suffix).
@item
It wraps the extracted content in an Org quote block (@samp{#+begin_quote} @dots{} @samp{#+end_quote}).
@item
It appends a citation of the form @samp{[cite:@@KEY, p. N]} after the quote block, where @samp{KEY} is the bib key obtained from the inherited @samp{Custom_ID} property and @samp{N} is the page number extracted from the original heading.
@end enumerate

This command is intended to be called with point on a ``Highlight on page N'' heading or its ``Contents'' child heading. It signals an error if no @samp{Custom_ID} property can be found by inheritance.

@node Merging annotations
@section Merging annotations

@findex org-noter-extras-merge-contents-with-next
When a highlighted passage spans two separate PDF annotations (for example, because the text crosses a page boundary or you highlighted in two steps), you end up with two adjacent ``Highlight on page'' headings. The command @code{org-noter-extras-merge-contents-with-next} combines them into a single annotation:

@enumerate
@item
With point on a ``Highlight on page N'' heading, it extracts the contents from both the current and the next annotation at the same outline level.
@item
It renames the current heading to ``Highlight on pages N--M'' (using an en dash), where M is the page number from the next annotation.
@item
It replaces the body of the current ``Contents'' subheading with the concatenation of both annotations' text.
@item
It deletes the next annotation subtree entirely.
@end enumerate

If point is not on a highlight heading, or if there is no next annotation at the same level, the command signals a user error.

@node Dehyphenation
@section Dehyphenation

@findex org-noter-extras-dehyphenate
@findex org-noter-extras-set-hyphen
Text extracted from PDFs often contains hyphens at the positions where the original layout engine broke words across lines. The command @code{org-noter-extras-dehyphenate} removes these artifacts by searching for the pattern ``letter-hyphen space letter'' and joining the two letter sequences. It operates on the current paragraph by default, or on the active region if one is set. The hyphen characters it searches for are defined by @code{org-noter-extras-dehyphenate-hyphens} (@ref{Dehyphenation characters}).

The command @code{org-noter-extras-set-hyphen} lets you interactively change the hyphen character used for dehyphenation. It presents a choice between @samp{-} (standard ASCII hyphen) and @samp{­} (soft hyphen) and updates @code{org-noter-extras-dehyphenate-hyphens} accordingly. This is useful when you encounter a PDF that uses an unusual character for line-break hyphens.

@node Page offset correction
@section Page offset correction

@findex org-noter-extras-highlight-offset
PDF page numbers and printed page numbers often differ because the PDF includes front matter (title page, table of contents, etc.) that is not counted in the book's own pagination. The command @code{org-noter-extras-highlight-offset} corrects all ``Highlight on page N'' headings in the current buffer by subtracting a user-specified offset from each page number.

The offset is defined as the PDF page number minus the book page number. For example, if the PDF viewer shows page 220 but the printed page says 210, the offset is 10. The command prompts for this value interactively. The offset is typically positive (PDF pages tend to be higher than book pages) but can be negative if needed.

@node Navigation
@section Navigation

@findex org-noter-extras-sync-next-note
@findex org-noter-extras-sync-prev-note
The standard @samp{org-noter} navigation commands @code{org-noter-sync-next-note} and @code{org-noter-sync-prev-note} move to the next or previous annotation and shift focus to the PDF viewer window. This can be disruptive when you want to review annotations in sequence while keeping focus on the Org notes buffer.

The command @code{org-noter-extras-sync-next-note} calls the standard @code{org-noter-sync-next-note} and then immediately switches focus back to the Org notes window using @code{other-window}. The command @code{org-noter-extras-sync-prev-note} does the same for backward navigation with @code{org-noter-sync-prev-note}. The PDF buffer still scrolls to the correct location; only the keyboard focus differs.

